Turnaround time: 1-2 business days Price: $16 What is a tax lien? A tax lien is a lien imposed by law upon a property to secure the payment of taxes. It is the government’s claim against all or some of your assets based on your failure to pay a tax debt on time. They may occur at the state or local level, or at the federal level. A tax lien may be imposed for delinquent taxes owed on real property or personal property, or as a result of failure to pay income taxes or other taxes. An IRS tax lien is a legal claim to your property as security or payment for your tax debt. What is a civil judgment? A civil judgment is a ruling against a defendant in a court of law. It can arise from small claims, unpaid debts, property damage as a result of negligence and so forth. Benefits of a tax lien and judgments search As of July 2017, the three major credit bureaus have begun to remove tax liens and judgments from credit reports . Because of that, it is a good idea to perform tax liens and judgments search if you are about to enter into a business venture with someone or if you are hiring someone for a financial position where fiscal responsibility is paramount. unverified_leads.scraped_content_preview: Cape Coral woman hopes someone can spare a kidney Crossword NEWS Cape Coral woman hopes someone can spare a kidney Melanie Payne mapayne@gannett.com Jan. 19, 2016 Updated Jan. 20, 2016, 9:52 a.m. ET Melneedsakidney.com . That’s Melissa Tuff’s website. She’s put her life and her plight online trying to raise money for a kidney transplant she can't afford. She hopes her story will move someone to step forward, and as she said, “give me their spare.” If Tuff can find a donor to part with one of two healthy kidneys and have it transplanted into her body, she’ll have four. The two she was born with are still in her. They gave out 20 years ago, when she was 16 and developed rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis, a life-threatening kidney disease. Within months she was in renal failure. She went on dialysis and on to the transplant list in Michigan, where she was living at the time. Over the next nine years Tuff endured 1,483 hemodialysis treatments. One Thursday night about 10 years ago, she decided to go to a casino. Her luck arrived before she got there. The University of Michigan Transplant Center called. She needed to come in right away. They had a kidney. “I feel like I’m living for both of us.” Tuff said she doesn’t know much about the man who died and whose kidney she received. He was 36 years old, the age Tuff is now. He had a head injury. She wrote a letter to his family but never heard back.  Within days of getting his kidney she felt great. Better than she had felt in a decade. Dialysis had taken a toll on Tuff. She was diagnosed with an enlarged heart. She lost calcium in her bones. Her muscles deteriorated and she suffered debilitating nausea, vomiting and leg cramps. Dialysis would make her blood pressure drop so low she would lose consciousness. Once she passed out while driving. Fortunately, she was stopped.
